const faqs = [{"question": "What's the difference between collagen peptides and collagen protein?", "answer": "Collagen peptides (also called hydrolyzed collagen) are collagen proteins that have been broken down into smaller, more easily absorbed fragments. Regular collagen protein has larger molecules that are harder to absorb. Hydrolyzed collagen peptides have higher bioavailability, meaning more of the product reaches your tissues."}, {"question": "Can your body actually absorb collagen supplements?", "answer": "Yes. Research has confirmed that hydrolyzed collagen peptides are absorbed through the intestinal wall and can be detected in the bloodstream. Di- and tripeptide fragments containing hydroxyproline are particularly well-absorbed and have been shown to accumulate in skin and cartilage tissue."}, {"question": "How long does it take to see results from collagen supplementation?", "answer": "Most clinical studies show measurable improvements in skin elasticity after 4–8 weeks and joint comfort after 8–12 weeks of consistent supplementation. Structural benefits (tendon, bone) may take 3–6 months to become apparent."}, {"question": "Should I take Type I, Type II, or Type III collagen?", "answer": "It depends on your primary health goal. Type I and III are best for skin, tendons, bones, and general structural support. Type II is specifically researched for cartilage and joint health. Many well-rounded products include multiple types. Your physician can recommend the most appropriate type based on your needs."}, {"question": "Are collagen peptide supplements the same as peptide therapy?", "answer": "No. Over-the-counter collagen peptide supplements are nutritional products that provide collagen building blocks. Clinical peptide therapy (BPC-157, TB-500, GHK-Cu) involves specific signaling peptides administered under physician supervision. They serve different purposes and work through different mechanisms."}, {"question": "How much collagen should I take daily?", "answer": "Most clinical studies used doses of 5–15 grams of hydrolyzed collagen per day. For joint health, studies on UC-II (undenatured Type II collagen) used much smaller doses of 40 mg per day. Optimal dosing depends on the specific product and your health goals."}, {"question": "Can I get enough collagen from food?", "answer": "Bone broth, chicken skin, fish skin, and organ meats contain collagen, but the collagen in food is not hydrolyzed, making absorption less efficient. Supplemental hydrolyzed collagen peptides offer higher bioavailability and more consistent dosing than dietary collagen sources."}];

